Diamesa tskhomelidzei Kownacki et Kownacka
was described by pharate male extracted from a mature pupa in the watercourses of the Terek River basin flowing down from the high mountain glaciers of the Caucasus (alt. 1800–3000 m a.s.l.), namely from the Chkheri River (Ortsveri Glacier) and the Suatisi River (Savitisi Glacier) in Georgia (
). The species was known only from the original description and was not identified from other areas of the Palaearctic region and, in our opinion, is endemic to the Caucasus (
). This assumption is confirmed by the finds of adult males and mature pupa of this species made by Dmitry Palatov in 2023 in the rivers at an altitude 2500–2630 m a.s.l., originating in the Kashkatash and Dzhankuat glaciers of Kabardino-Balkaria Republic of Russia (Elbrus Region) and which also belong to the Terek River basin.

Abdomen. Tergite I with shagreen in anterior third. Tergites II–VII with shagreen in anterior two thirds or half, tergite VIII almost all with shagreen. Sternites I–III without shagreen, sternites IV–VIII with rare shagreen and IX without shagreen. Tergites I–VIII with posterior transverse row spines, number of these spines on tergites respectively—16: 14: 17: 15: 14: 15: 13: 11 (
Figs 9–10
). Number of posterior transverse row spines of sternites III–VIII respectively—16: 14: 14: 11: 8: 8–9. Segments I–VIII with 4 pairs of lateral setae, 48–64 μm long. Segments II–VIII with spine-like process on posterolateral corner (
Fig. 10
). Anal lobe with 3 yellow anal macrosetae, 249–248 μm long, slightly curved in distal part and pointed. Male genital sac extended beyond anal lobe (
Figs 7
, 
10
).
